	<!-- Simple types derived from layout.mod elements -->

	<xs:simpleType name="distance-type">
		<xs:annotation>
			<xs:documentation>The distance-type defines what type of distance is being defined in a &lt;distance&gt; element. Values include:

- beam
- hyphen

This is left as a string so that other application-specific types can be defined, but it is made a separate type so that it can be redefined more strictly.

The beam type represents the distance between beam. The hyphen type represents the distance between hyphens in lyrics.</xs:documentation>
		</xs:annotation>
		<xs:restriction base="xs:token"/>
	</xs:simpleType>

	<xs:simpleType name="glyph-type">
		<xs:annotation>
			<xs:documentation>The glyph-type defines what type of glyph is being defined in a &lt;glyph&gt; element. Values include:

- quarter-rest
- g-clef-ottava-bassa
- c-clef
- f-clef
- percussion-clef
- octave-shift-up-8
- octave-shift-down-8
- octave-shift-continue-8
- octave-shift-down-15
- octave-shift-up-15
- octave-shift-continue-15
- octave-shift-down-22
- octave-shift-up-22
- octave-shift-continue-22

This is left as a string so that other application-specific types can be defined, but it is made a separate type so that it can be redefined more strictly.

A quarter-rest type specifies the glyph to use when a note has a &lt;rest&gt; element and a &lt;type&gt; value of quarter.

The c-clef, f-clef, and percussion-clef types specify the glyph to use when a clef &lt;sign&gt; element value is C, F, or percussion respectively.

The g-clef-ottava-bassa type specifies the glyph to use when a clef &lt;sign&gt; element value is G and the &lt;clef-octave-change&gt; element value is -1.

The octave-shift types specify the glyph to use when an &lt;octave-shift&gt; type attribute value is up, down, or continue and the &lt;octave-shift&gt; size attribute value is 8, 15, or 22.</xs:documentation>
		</xs:annotation>
		<xs:restriction base="xs:token"/>
	</xs:simpleType>

	<xs:simpleType name="line-width-type">
		<xs:annotation>
			<xs:documentation>The line-width-type defines what type of line is being defined in a &lt;line-width&gt; element. Values include:

- beam
- bracket
- dashes
- enclosure
- ending
- extend
- heavy barline
- leger
- light barline
- octave shift
- pedal
- slur middle
- slur tip
- staff
- stem
- tie middle
- tie tip
- tuplet bracket
- wedge

This is left as a string so that other application-specific types can be defined, but it is made a separate type so that it can be redefined more strictly.</xs:documentation>
		</xs:annotation>
		<xs:restriction base="xs:token"/>
	</xs:simpleType>

	<xs:simpleType name="margin-type">
		<xs:annotation>
			<xs:documentation>The margin-type type specifies whether margins apply to even page, odd pages, or both.</xs:documentation>
		</xs:annotation>
		<xs:restriction base="xs:token">
			<xs:enumeration value="odd">
				<xs:annotation>
					<xs:documentation>Margins apply to odd pages only.</xs:documentation>
				</xs:annotation>
			</xs:enumeration>
			<xs:enumeration value="even">
				<xs:annotation>
					<xs:documentation>Margins apply to even pages only.</xs:documentation>
				</xs:annotation>
			</xs:enumeration>
			<xs:enumeration value="both">
				<xs:annotation>
					<xs:documentation>Margins apply to both even and odd pages.</xs:documentation>
				</xs:annotation>
			</xs:enumeration>
		</xs:restriction>
	</xs:simpleType>

